         <h1>Marguerite Duras, 81, Author Who Explored Love and Sex </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Marguerite Duras , author of the best-selling novel " The Lover " and one of the most widely read French writers of the postwar era , died today at her home in Paris . <br><blue>2</blue>She was 81 . <br><blue>3</blue>Miss Duras , who was also a prolific playwright , film maker and screenwriter , was best known for the way she used her early life in French Indochina as the inspiration for many of her works , including " The Lover , " the story of her clandestine teen-age romance with a wealthy young Chinese man . <br><blue>4</blue>Yet perhaps what most characterized her 53-year literary career was her simple , terse writing style , as if language itself were merely a vehicle for conveying passion and desire , pain and despair . <br><blue>5</blue>The mysteries of love and sex consumed her , but she had no room for sentimentality in her works , or indeed , in her life . <br><blue>6</blue>I write about love , yes , but not about tenderness , " she said in a 1990 interview . <br><blue>7</blue>" I do n't like tender people . <br><blue>8</blue>I myself am very harsh . <br><blue>9</blue>When I love someone , I desire them . <br><blue>10</blue>But tenderness supposes the exclusion of desire . " <br><blue>11</blue>Ever provocative in her use of language , she always bowed to the supremacy of words . <br><blue>12</blue>" Acting does n't bring anything to a text , " Miss Duras wrote of her work for cinema and theater . <br><blue>13</blue>" On the contrary , it detracts from it -- lessens its immediacy and depth , weakens its muscles and dilutes its blood . " <br><blue>14</blue>In the theater , this seemed to matter little , and her plays continue to be performed regularly in France . <br><blue>15</blue>However , despite the enormous success of her screenplay for Alain Resnais 's 1960 classic , " Hiroshima , Mon Amour , " few of the 19 movies she wrote and directed herself did well , not least because words often entirely replaced action . <br><blue>16</blue>Until her 70th birthday , her novels had a loyal albeit small readership . <br><blue>17</blue>With the publication of " The Lover " in 1984 , however , Miss Duras reached a mass audience in France and abroad . <br><blue>18</blue>The book sold more than two million copies and was made into a well-received film in 1992 by Jean-Jacques Annaud . <br><blue>19</blue>Because she considered her words to be sacrosanct , she often had stormy dealings with movie directors who adapted her novels , among them Peter Brook , Tony Richardson and Jules Dassin . <br><blue>20</blue>And when Mr. Annaud altered her screenplay for " The Lover , " Miss Duras broke with him and turned her text into yet another semi-autobiographical novel , " The Lover From Northern China . " <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>theater</m_str> (12_21) 	<m_str>the theater</m_str> (14_2) 	<br><blue>2(6)</blue>: <m_str>I</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (7_2) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>myself</m_str> (8_2) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (9_2) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (9_6) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>language itself were merely a vehicle for conveying passion and desire , pain and despair</m_str> (4_20) 	<m_str>itself</m_str> (4_21) 	<br><blue>4(1)</blue>: <m_str>her life</m_str> (5_25) 	<br><blue>5(33)</blue>: <m_str>her</m_str> (15_8) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (16_2) 	<m_str>Marguerite Duras</m_str> (1_1) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (16_6) 	<m_str>she</m_str> (15_29) 	<m_str>herself</m_str> (15_33) 	<m_str>She</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (1_30) 	<m_str>Miss Duras</m_str> (17_14) 	<m_str>Miss Duras , who was also a prolific playwright , film maker and screenwriter</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (11_4) 	<m_str>she</m_str> (11_9) 	<m_str>she</m_str> (19_2) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (19_4) 	<m_str>she</m_str> (3_22) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (4_6) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (3_24) 	<m_str>she</m_str> (19_10) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (4_11) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (3_36) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (19_20) 	<m_str>Miss Duras</m_str> (12_12) 	<m_str>her</m_str> (20_6) 	<